    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-08-09T09:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-08-09T09:00:00-05:00" n="598"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d598">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">741D.62115/8–945: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Ireland</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gray</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Dublin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-08-09T15:00:00+01:00"
                            >August 9, 1945—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 7:15 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>173. Re Legation’s telegram 172; 39 to London. Believe point raised by Winant
                    regards paragraph 4 of our suggestions for note requesting repatriation of
                    certain German categories well taken. Our draft was pronounced tentatively as
                    basis for discussion and constructive criticism. Further consideration here
                    inclines us to view that paragraph 1 of our 172 should be based on explicit
                    statement of de Valera that as far as it lay with Irish Govt Eire was externally
                    associated with British Commonwealth. The gist of paragraph 1 would therefore
                    read substantially as follows.</p>
                <quote rend="blockquote">
                    <p>The United Nations regard with satisfaction the recent statement of the Irish
                        Prime Minister that insofar as it may lie with the Irish Govt Eire is
                        externally associated with the British Commonwealth of Nations. With the
                        termination of the war in Europe Irish neutrality is no longer in issue and
                        United Nations in which all states of British Commonwealth have membership
                        may confidently expect the cooperative action implied in such
                        association.</p>
                </quote>
                <p>Sent Dept 173 repeated London 40.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gray</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
